

Arrow Function:
--------------

 => With arrow functions, you can write functions in a shorter way, which makes code easier to read and write.
 => arrow functions implicity bind the this keyword to the enclosing scopes, so you don't need to use bind(), 
 call(), or apply() to bind it to the current object.

 const button = document.querySelector('button');

 button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('Button clicked');
 });


 const numbers = [1, 2, 3]
 const squaredNumbers = numbers.map(x => x * x);
 console.log(squaredNumbers )
